Absolutely! For sqlx with PostgreSQL and async, using `sqlx::postgres::PgPool` is typical. Here’s an example of how to setup and use it safely:

```rust
use sqlx::{PgPool, postgres::PgPoolOptions};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), sqlx::Error> {
    let pool = PgPoolOptions::new()
        .max_connections(5)
        .connect("postgres://user:pass@localhost/dbname")
        .await?;
    // Use pool to execute queries
}
```
One common newbie mistake is forgetting `.await` on `.connect()`. That won't compile, so be careful!

